Page 1: Latency Fundamentals
Latency:
Also known as delay.
Definition: Latency is the time taken for data to travel from the client to the server and the server back to the client.
In simple terms, it is a delay in computation.
Low Latency (↓): Results in a faster response time (↑).
Example: If you send a request to a server and it responds in 1000 Nanoseconds, the latency is 1000 Ns.
Note: Maximum latency is usually measured in ms (milliseconds).
Real-world Example: When you click "submit" or any button to load something new, the time taken to load is the latency.
Latency defines how long it takes for an entire message to completely arrive at its destination from the moment the first bit was sent.
Components of Latency (T):
Latency is the sum of all the following delays:
Transmission delay
Propagation delay
Queuing delay
Processing delay

