Page 4: Queuing & Processing Delays
Queuing Delay:
The third component of latency.
It is the time needed for each intermediate or end device to hold a message before it can be processed.
This represents the time a message spends in memory waiting for its turn.
Important: Queuing time is not a fixed factor; it changes based on the load imposed on the network.
Processing Delay:
How much time a node takes to process the message.
The time taken to process a request that has been sent by a device.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Page 5: Throughput
Throughput:
Throughput is the actual amount of data successfully transferred per second.
Theoretical vs. Real: Even if a network has high bandwidth, the real data transfer rate might be lower due to congestion or delays.
Throughput represents real performance, showing how much data was actually received by a device.
Example:
Bandwidth = 100 Mbps
Actual transfer = 70 Mbps
Throughput = 70 Mbps
High throughput results in great overall speed.
Summary Comparison:
Latency: Delay in communication.
Bandwidth: Maximum data capacity.
Throughput: Actual data transfer rate.